{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"2d24ce21-55f9-4efa-8610-888e6c5867fa","content":"Run **`dotnet workload update`**. Here's why:\n\n- **`dotnet workload update`** — Downloads and installs the **latest versions** of all installed workloads to match your current SDK. After an SDK update, this is what brings workloads (like `maui`) back in sync.\n\n- **`dotnet workload repair`** — Re-installs workloads **at their current versions**. It fixes corrupted installations but won't pull newer versions needed by a newer SDK.\n\n**TL;DR:** SDK went up → workloads need to go up too → `dotnet workload update`.\n\n```bash\ndotnet workload update\n```\n\nIf you still hit issues afterward, run `dotnet workload list` to confirm the `maui` workload is installed and up to date.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"1f165724-f5d2-4374-942f-cd70367d4916","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about the difference between `dotnet workload update` and `dotnet workload repair` to fix build issues after a .NET SDK update. This is a general .NET knowledge question — I don't need to explore any codebase for this.","outputTokens":258,"requestId":"B80B:18AE3E:11AA30:17394C:69FFD72B"},"id":"5fcaa352-6935-48f3-ac51-52bb65cf59fc","timestamp":"2026-05-10T00:54:10.524Z","parentId":"df04be57-1201-46c1-acdc-af247796e4ef"}
